{
  "text": "NMT is a ubiquitously distributed eukaryotic enzyme accounting for the A'-myristoylation of a substantial number of proteins, some of which are required for signal transduction and regulatory functions important in cellular growth control (e.g., serine/threonine/tyrosine kinases, protein phosphatases, and Gproteins). Thus, NMT appears to be a critical cellular enzyme, the disruption of which has been shown to be lethal in the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae [CITATION_1] and in the fungi Cryptococcus neoformans and Candida albicans [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Considering the cumulative genetic mutations involved in carcinogenesis [CITATION_4] , including changes in oncogenes that could result in altered expression and/or function(s) of A'-myristoylated oncoproteins (8), it is also likely that NMT is functional in aberrant cellular processes that account for progression to the malignant cell phenotype. To the extent that NMT and/or A'-myristoylproteins are found to be involved in carcinogenesis, protein A'-myristoylation should be examined as a possible chemotherapeutic target for cancer (2) . However, progress in furthering this goal will require 1) establishing an A'-myristoylation causal and/or dependency relationship with cancer, 2) an understanding of the mechanism(s) regulating protein A'-myristoylation in mammalian cells, and 3) developing approaches to selectively interfere with critical A'-myristoylation steps while avoiding general toxicity.",
  "citation_candidates": [
